  - q: "How much does estate planning cost in Nevada?"
    a: "Costs vary based on complexity. A basic will may cost $500-$1,500, while a comprehensive trust-based plan typically ranges from $2,000-$5,000+. We provide transparent pricing during your free consultation."
  - q: "Do I need a trust or just a will?"
    a: "It depends on your assets, family situation, and goals. Trusts avoid probate and offer more control, but a will may be sufficient for simpler estates. Jordan will help you determine the right approach."
  - q: "How often should I update my estate plan?"
    a: "Review your plan every 3-5 years or after any major life event — marriage, divorce, birth of a child, significant asset changes, or moves between states."
  - q: "What happens if I die without an estate plan in Nevada?"
    a: "Nevada's intestacy laws determine how your assets are distributed — which may not align with your wishes. Your estate may also go through probate, adding time and expense."
